UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1549
1 tuberculosis examined and treated according to administrative regulations of the
2 Cabinet for Health and Family Services. Nothing in this section shall be construed
3 to require the testing for tuberculosis of any child whose parent or guardian is
4 opposed to such testing, and who objects by a written sworn statement to the testing
5 for tuberculosis of the child on religious grounds. However, in a suspected case of
6 tuberculosis, a local health department may require testing of this child.
7 (3) All public or private primary or secondary schools, and preschool programs shall
8 require a current immunization certificate for any child enrolled as a regular
9 attendee, as provided by administrative regulation of the Cabinet for Health and
10 Family Services, promulgated under KRS Chapter 13A, to be on file within two (2)
11 weeks of the child's attendance.
12 (4) [All public or private primary schools shall require a current immunization
13 certificate for hepatitis B for any child enrolled as a regular attendee in the sixth
14 grade, as provided by administrative regulation of the Cabinet for Health and
15 Family Services, promulgated under KRS Chapter 13A, to be on file within two (2)
16 weeks of the child's attendance.
17 (5) ]For each child cared for in a day-care center, certified family child-care home, or
18 any other licensed facility which cares for children, a current immunization
19 certificate, as provided by administrative regulation of the Cabinet for Health and
20 Family Services, promulgated under KRS Chapter 13A, shall be on file in the
21 center, home, or facility within thirty (30) days of entrance into the program or
22 admission to the facility.
23 (5)[(6)] Any forms relating to exemption from immunization requirements shall be
24 available at public or private primary or secondary schools, preschool programs,
25 day-care centers, certified family child-care homes, or other licensed facilities
26 which care for children.
